export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"Four territories","intro":"The category defaults are rejected as primary signal: Santorini blue, resort turquoise, safari ochre, foliage red. They are not wrong — they are unearned without specific cultural grounding. Each palette is sourced from three places only — the territory's material culture, its specific light condition, and the historical pigment tradition available to the people of the place. The test is recognition: someone who has been here should know the palette without seeing the label."},"II":{"title":"More territories, further from the postcard","intro":"This volume pushes harder against the category default. Tokyo is not sakura pink; Lisbon is not azulejo blue as primary; Iceland is not aurora green; Kerala is not backwater turquoise. Each is a specific hour and a specific surface — read the kicker before the swatches. As before: every swatch names its material, pigment, or light source. The hierarchy is enforced. The refuses line is part of the spec, not editorial flavour."},"III":{"title":"More interiors, mostly at night or under weather","intro":"Volume III leans inward. Three of the four territories are interiors — a felt-walled ger, a Viennese kaffeehaus, an adobe house seen between mountain stops — and the fourth is a Faroese harbour so thickly fogged that it reads as an interior anyway. Light here is small, local, and almost always from below or behind. As before: every swatch names its source. The hierarchy is enforced. The refuses line names the colour that would betray the territory."},"IV":{"title":"Shorelines, four hours of working light","intro":"Coastal palettes are the most pre-conquered category in the colour world: resort turquoise, postcard cobalt, white-sand cream. Every territory in this volume refuses one of those defaults outright, because the real working coast — a Newfoundland outport, a Mumbai koliwada, a Breton quay, a Hokkaido kelp shore — does not look like the brochure. Each palette names its hour, its weather, and the material being worked. Primary by surface area, secondary by frequency, accent by punctuation. The refuses line names the postcard."},"V":{"title":"Thinner air, three months from peak season","intro":"Altitude does things to colour: less atmosphere to scatter blue, more UV to bleach reds, ground that holds heat unevenly between sun and shadow. These four territories are sampled in the working season, not the photographer's golden hour: a Khumbu teahouse at supper, Cuzco's plaza in winter morning, a Dolomites refuge at season's end, a Ladakhi monastery at dusk. Each one refuses an obvious tourist signifier — saturated red on the prayer flag, the woven-textile rainbow, the apres-ski neon, the saffron-robe orange — and finds the colour in the wall, the smoke, the stove, the snow."},"VI":{"title":"Cities, after dark, off the tourist hour","intro":"Cities at night are mostly sodium and shadow. The brand colours that work at noon — Buenos Aires's blue-and-white, Istanbul's tile, Hanoi's lacquer, Tbilisi's gold — recede; the working palette is the streetlamp and the asphalt. Each of these four refuses the daytime cliché: the tango red, the Marmara turquoise, the jungle green, the cathedral gold. The dominant in every case is a working surface, not a brand."},"VII":{"title":"Markets, working hours, not the food-tour version","intro":"Markets are the densest single source of material culture in any city — and the most over-pictured. The strategy here is to find the dominant working colour, not the most photogenic stall. Counter wood. Vendor apron. Drying mat. Tile back-of-house. Each palette names the pigment, the textile, or the cured material that anchors it. Pagoda gold, designer azulejo, rainbow ethnic-textile, Mediterranean cobalt — all refused in their place."},"VIII":{"title":"Trains, four hours not on the brochure","intro":"Train palettes are mostly engineered — the upholstery and the panel are spec'd by a transport authority, not by light. So the strategy is to find the engineering palette and then admit the one or two outside colours that survive the journey: the window, the platform, the conductor's uniform, the dining-car cloth. Each of these refuses the easy outside-the-train postcard — the aurora, the Cycladic blue, the Outback turquoise, the spice quarter. The dominant is always something the railway chose."},"IX":{"title":"Rooms made for ritual, at the hour the ritual happens","intro":"Sacred spaces are designed for one moment: midnight, dawn, dusk, the hour the procession arrives. Sampling them outside that hour gives a museum colour; sampling them during it gives a working colour. Every palette here is the used version of the space. Each refuses an outsider's signifier — cathedral cool blue, candy cherry-blossom pink, orientalist lavender, Halloween orange-and-black. The dominant is always the surface the rite is performed on."},"X":{"title":"Deserts, four very different reasons nothing grows","intro":"Deserts get treated as one category; they are not. The Empty Quarter is sand and sky, Wadi Rum is sandstone and basalt, the Skeleton Coast is fog and bone, the Great Salt Lake is hypersaline brine. Each makes a different palette refusal mandatory. Specifically: oil-money gold, Petra-rose monochrome, safari-poster orange, lagoon-turquoise. Each is the wrong colour for its territory and is named in the refuses line."},"XI":{"title":"Forests, no fairy tales, just the ground cover and the canopy","intro":"Forest palettes are almost always rendered as green-on-green; in working forests, green is rarely the dominant. The Tongass is gloom; the Schwarzwald is canopy-dark; the Atchafalaya is grey; the Kamchatkan taiga is overcast. Each refuses an external marketing colour — calendar teal, Grimm-tourism red, neon-bayou magenta, Kamchatka-poster glacier-teal. The dominant is what you actually walk on or stand under."},"XII":{"title":"The wrong week to be there","intro":"Every territory has a wrong week — the season the brochures don't show. Plum-rain in a Chinese tea region. Latvian winter. Typhoon afternoon on Okinawa. July fog at Point Reyes. The palettes that show up in those weeks are the territory's truer ones, because nobody is curating them. Each refuses the in-season postcard: spring cherry blossom, Baltic-summer blue, Okinawa-resort turquoise, California-poster sunshine. The dominant is the weather the photographer skipped."}};
